    "content_hash": "sha256:d43dae00d9d62505e8b020c63d4a1668297cdc3f1ce7137bc1e01a74e578e7c6",
    "summary": "The Chola Dynasty (c. 9th–13th centuries AD in its medieval form) was the greatest Tamil empire — a South Indian naval power that at its peak controlled Sri Lanka, the Maldives, and launched raids into [[event:2167|Srivijaya's]] territory in Southeast Asia, making it the dominant power of the Bay of Bengal. The dynasty had ancient roots, but its medieval period began under Vijayalaya (c. 848 AD), who established the Chola capital at Thanjavur (Tanjore). Under Rajaraja I (r. 985–1014 AD) and his son Rajendra I (r. 1014–1044 AD), the Cholas reached their peak power.\n\nRajaraja I constructed the magnificent Brihadeeswarar Temple in Thanjavur (1010 AD) — a 66-meter vimana (tower) that remains one of the greatest examples of South Indian temple architecture, and one of the few Dravidian temples to cast no shadow at noon due to its precise vertical construction. Rajendra I sent a naval expedition (1025 AD) that raided Srivijayan ports in Sumatra and the Malay Peninsula, establishing Chola commercial dominance in the Bay of Bengal trade. The Chola administrative system — with its village assemblies, temple-centered local governance, and bureaucratic organization — is considered one of the most sophisticated administrative achievements of medieval India. Chola bronze casting, particularly the Nataraja (dancing Shiva) bronzes, represents the apex of south Indian sacred art, with the Nataraja icon becoming one of the most recognized images in world art.",
